 "components": {
  "instruction": "You are tasked with classifying short customer messages related to banking or financial issues into exactly one, highly specific support category based only on the content of the customer's text. \n\nInput Format:\n- You will receive a JSON object with a single key \"text\" and a short customer message as its value.\n  Example input: { \"text\": \"<customer message>\" }\n\nTask Steps:\n1. Carefully read the customer message, focusing entirely on explicit information provided in the text. Do not infer or assume any details that are not directly stated.\n2. Match the issue, question, or request described to exactly one category label from the fixed list provided below, choosing the most specific and directly relevant category based strictly on what is stated.\n3. Output only the category label as plain text. Do not give explanations, extra text, or formatting—just the raw category string.\n\nKey Guidance and Important Domain Rules:\n- Select only from the provided category list; do not invent new categories.\n- Use only keywords and direct context from the customer’s message. Do not use prior knowledge or outside information.\n- If the message could fit more than one category, always pick the most specific or narrow label that directly addresses the customer's explicit request or issue.\n- For questions about receiving money (including salaries, transfers in any currency, etc.), always select 'receiving_money', even if the message mentions the type or source of funds.\n- For card delivery, PIN mailer queries, or logistics about getting the physical card, use 'get_physical_card' (including issues/questions about how or when the card or PIN will arrive).\n- Do not select 'passcode_forgotten' unless the customer explicitly mentions forgetting or the need to reset their passcode or PIN (the words forgot, reset, or similar must occur).\n- For fees: If a customer questions a fee for making a transfer, use 'transfer_fee_charged'. If it's about a card payment/service fee, use 'card_payment_fee_charged'. Pay strict attention to the context to distinguish these.\n- For transfers or top-ups in progress, not yet completed, or delayed, use 'pending_transfer' or 'pending_top_up' as appropriate (the customer must indicate the action is still processing, waiting, or delayed).\n- If a transfer failed outright (not pending or delayed), use 'failed_transfer'.\n- For attempts to add money by cash or cheque (not bank transfer or card), use 'top_up_by_cash_or_cheque'.\n- For issues about automated or recurring money deposits, use 'automatic_top_up'.\n- For card transactions that the customer does not recognize or suspects are fraudulent, use 'card_payment_not_recognised'.\n- If a fee is questioned specifically regarding a card payment, even if referred to as a 'service fee', use 'card_payment_fee_charged'.\n- For money refunds or reversals of card payments, use 'reverted_card_payment?'.\n- For concerns about using the app to exchange currency, use 'exchange_via_app'. For all other exchange rate queries, use 'exchange_rate'.\n- For requests/questions about identity verification or having trouble completing it, use 'verify_my_identity'.\n- For requests/questions about verifying or providing proof of the source of funds, use 'verify_source_of_funds'.\n- For failed or declined ATM/cash withdrawals, use 'declined_cash_withdrawal'.\n- For questions about adding funds by card, use 'topping_up_by_card'.\n- For requesting a single-use (disposable) virtual card, use 'get_disposable_virtual_card'.\n- For queries about bank transfer into the account (not cash, cheque, or receiving in general), use 'transfer_into_account'.\n- For issues where the customer cannot add or pay a specific recipient (beneficiary), use 'beneficiary_not_allowed'.\n- For issues about a transfer that has been or needs to be cancelled, use 'cancel_transfer'.\n- For questions about transfer timing (e.g., \"how long does a transfer take?\"), use 'transfer_timing'.\n\nSupport Categories List:\n- automatic_top_up\n- balance_not_updated_after_bank_transfer\n- beneficiary_not_allowed\n- cancel_transfer\n- card_payment_fee_charged\n- card_payment_not_recognised\n- declined_cash_withdrawal\n- exchange_rate\n- exchange_via_app\n- failed_transfer\n- get_disposable_virtual_card\n- get_physical_card\n- passcode_forgotten\n- pending_top_up\n- pending_transfer\n- receiving_money\n- reverted_card_payment?\n- top_up_by_cash_or_cheque\n- top_up_reverted\n- topping_up_by_card\n- transfer_fee_charged\n- transfer_into_account\n- transfer_timing\n- verify_my_identity\n- verify_source_of_funds\n\nOutput Requirements:\n- Output only the selected category label (no explanations, formatting, or extra content).\n\nGeneralizable Strategy:\n- Always classify based solely on explicit textual evidence presented; abstain from generalization or assumptions.\n- In cases where category choice is ambiguous, select the most specific category that fully contains the customer's described need or issue.\n\nExample:\nInput:\n{ \"text\": \"My payment was reversed, is there a reason for this?\" }\nOutput:\nreverted_card_payment?"
 },
